  <ul class="comments by_time"  style="display: none">
      
      <li class="ctsh clearfix" data-cid="22970581">
        <div class="ilst">
          <a href="https://www.douban.com/people/gengshi/"><img src="https://img3.doubanio.com/icon/u6327920-2.jpg" alt="耕石" class="" /></a>
        </div>
        <div class="con">
          <div class="nlst">
            <h3>
              <div class="note-toggle rr">
                <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/22970581/" class="note-unfolder">展开</a>
                <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="note-folder">收起</a>
              </div>
              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/22970581/" class="">第98页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/gengshi/" class=" " title="耕石">耕石</a>
                (wy)
              
                <span class="allstar50" title="力荐"></span>
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="22970581">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">Discussing from aspects of domestic and international conditions,  Wanghui's article provides a critique of Chinese neoliberalism. 
The Chinese neoliberalism is a combination of political authority and economic capital. Of course, as Harvey and Ong argue, that, one typical and essential feature of neoliberalism is that joint of political authoritarianism and free market policy. What is significan...</span>
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/22970581/">(<span class="">3回应</span>)</a>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2012-12-06 00:16</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                Discussing from aspects of domestic and international conditions,  Wanghui's article provides a critique of Chinese neoliberalism. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The Chinese neoliberalism is a combination of political authority and economic capital. Of course, as Harvey and Ong argue, that, one typical and essential feature of neoliberalism is that joint of political authoritarianism and free market policy. What is significant of the Chinese neoliberalism is that such a combination comes out of the previous authoritative governance in the form of continuation, rather than a rupture. To understand this, Wanghui suggests we go back to the socialist period of China. In the socialist China, the dominant ideology is the ideology of equality, which is based on the institutionalized inequality and hierarchy between the urban and the rural. The reform and open up policy, as a reflection on socialism as resistance to the capitalist model of modernization, has preserved the ideology of equality and adopt the capitalist model of modernization. The consequence of this adjustment is the development of economy, but even more importantly, the unleash of the institutionalized inequality. What this change means is that the gap between private companies and state-own companies within the city, and the gap between the urban population and the rural population have enlarged increasingly, in terms of their social status and economic income, which consequently causes social disturbance.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The 1989 movement is a manifestation of this social disturbance. It contains participants with conflicting interests claims. For example, the new rich wants to push forward the privatization of public property and marketization, while the factory workers want to shrink, if not close it at all, the gap of income and social status differences.  The failure of bringing up a workable project paralyzed the whole movement. But, the movement is not a total failure if we think about the radical marketization followed after the suppression. It is the factory workers and peasants who are the losers. Factory workers lose their jobs and peasants lose their land as urbanization and marketization expand.  <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The movement is a failure in the sense that the inherent organic connections that bridge the common people, the elites and the state that are crucial in establishing a civil society are cut off by the government violently. The connections have to be reconstructed in order to defend society against the invasion of Chinese neocapitalism, which under peaceful conditions asking for free trade and marketization, under unstable conditions asking for protection and intervention of the state, and facing global market, asking for the total withdraw of state power from market. The connections are reviving at least within the intellectual community when they reflect on the discourse of modernization, Westernization, and finally free market in front of global crisis such as Asian financial crisis and the Yugoslavia crisis. 

                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







<div class="rec-sec">

    <span class="rec">

<a href="https://www.douban.com/accounts/register?reason=collect" class="j a_show_login lnk-sharing lnk-douban-sharing">推荐</a>
</span>
</div>

                  </div>
                <div class="pl col-time">
                  <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/22970581/#comments">3回应</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
                  2012-12-06 00:16
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      
      <li class="ctsh clearfix" data-cid="22422244">
        <div class="ilst">
